  <div style="width:98%;display:table-cell">
   <A HREF="https://ajammc.com/2014/07/08/rewriting-hafez-persian-poetry/" TARGET="news"><div class="newshead">Rewriting Hafez: Re-theorizing Untranslatability in Persian Poetry</div></a><br>
   <A HREF="https://ajammc.com/2014/07/08/rewriting-hafez-persian-poetry/" TARGET="news"><img src="http://www.payvand.com/news/20/may/Re-theorizing-Untranslatability-in-Persian-Poetry-i.jpg" hspace="4" align="right" width="200"></a>
   <div class="newssum">Near Eastern thinkers, perhaps as early as al-Ja&#7717;i&#7827;, the eighth century Arab writer and polemicist, have commented on the problem of literary translation, particularly concerning poetry. While al-Ja&#7717;i&#7827; points to broad challenges encountered in translating lyrical poetry, he gives more weight to translation as an end result, characterized by various layers of loss consequent to this linguistic transfer. One implication of reading translation merely as a product is to indict translation as an intellectual enterprise-as often has been done-and place it within the reductionist model of &#34;betrayal&#34; versus &#34;faithfulness.&#34; -Aria Fani, Ajam 5/27/20</div>
  </div>
